\begin_layout Standard
In this appendix we present a short overview of the symmetry properties
 of bulk semiconductor wavefunction, expressed in the mathematical formulation
 of the group theory.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Let 
\begin_inset Formula $H(\mathbf{r})=T+U(\mathbf{r})$
\end_inset

 be the Hamiltonian in 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:zero_center_Bloch_Equation"

\end_inset

 with the kinetic operator 
\begin_inset Formula $T$
\end_inset

 and crystal potential 
\begin_inset Formula $U(\mathbf{r})$
\end_inset

, and let 
\begin_inset Formula $G$
\end_inset

 be the point group
\begin_inset Foot
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
A 
\emph on
crystallographic point group
\emph default
 is a set of symmetry operations, like rotations or reflections, that leave
 a point fixed while moving each atom of the crystal to the position of
 an atom of the same kind.
 That is, an infinite crystal would look exactly the same before and after
 any of the operations in its point group.
 In the classification of crystals, each point group corresponds to a crystal
 class.
\end_layout

\end_inset

 of the crystal such that the symmetry operator 
\begin_inset Formula $g\in G$
\end_inset

, the crystal potential is invariant, i.e.
 
\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
\forall g\in G,\,\,\, U(g^{-1}\mathbf{r})=U(\mathbf{r}).\end{equation}

\end_inset

The kinetic operator 
\begin_inset Formula $T$
\end_inset

 is naturally invariant under the action of the elements in the point group
 
\begin_inset Formula $G$
\end_inset

.
 Assuming that 
\begin_inset Formula $\psi(\mathbf{r})$
\end_inset

 is an eigenfunction of 
\begin_inset Formula $H$
\end_inset

 with 
\begin_inset Formula $H(\mathbf{r})\psi(\mathbf{r})=E\psi(\mathbf{r})$
\end_inset

 and applying the symmetry operator 
\begin_inset Formula $g$
\end_inset

, leads to 
\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
H(g^{-1}\mathbf{r})\psi(g^{-1}\mathbf{r})=H(\mathbf{r})\psi(g^{-1}\mathbf{r})=E\psi(g^{-1}\mathbf{r}).\end{equation}

\end_inset

Obviously 
\begin_inset Formula $\psi'(\mathbf{r})=\psi(g^{-1}\mathbf{r})$
\end_inset

 is also an eigenfunction of the Hamiltonian operator 
\begin_inset Formula $H(\mathbf{r})$
\end_inset

 with eigenvalue 
\begin_inset Formula $E$
\end_inset

.
 The wavefunction 
\begin_inset Formula $\psiâ€²(\mathbf{r})$
\end_inset

 might be the same wavefunction as 
\begin_inset Formula $\psi(\mathbf{r})$
\end_inset

 or might be linearly independent.
 Applying all symmetry operations 
\begin_inset Formula $g\in G$
\end_inset

 therefore results in a set of wavefunctions with the same eigenvalue 
\begin_inset Formula $E$
\end_inset

, spanning a function space
\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
I_{\psi}=\left\{ \psi'(\mathbf{r})|\psi'(\mathbf{r})=\psi'(g^{-1}\mathbf{r})\,\,\,\forall g\in G\right\} .\end{equation}

\end_inset

Now, the point group 
\begin_inset Formula $G$
\end_inset

 is a closed group, meaning that for 
\begin_inset Formula $g,\, f\in G:\, gf\in G$
\end_inset

.
 Therefore, the function space 
\begin_inset Formula $I_{\psi}$
\end_inset

 is invariant under the action of 
\begin_inset Formula $G$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
\psi(\mathbf{r})\in I_{\psi}\Rightarrow\psi(g^{-1}\mathbf{r})\in I_{\psi}.\end{equation}

\end_inset

Suppose that 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\{ \psi_{0},\psi_{1},\ldots,\psi_{N}\right\} $
\end_inset

 is the basis of the subspace 
\begin_inset Formula $I_{\psi}$
\end_inset

, which is assumed to be of the dimension 
\begin_inset Formula $N$
\end_inset

.
 The basis is denoted as being the
\emph on
 irreducible representation
\emph default
 of the group 
\begin_inset Formula $G$
\end_inset

.
 The desirable property deduced from group theory is that for every symmetry
 group, there are only a few distinct irreducible representations.
 Every irreducible representation describes an unique way how wavefunctions
 are transformed under the action of the elements of a symmetry group 
\begin_inset Formula $G$
\end_inset

.
 Therefore, the eigenfunctions of the crystal Hamiltonian 
\begin_inset Formula $H$
\end_inset

 can be classified according to the irreducible representation they form.
 It is clear that each eigenfunction does only belong to one irreducible
 representation and it is clear that eigenfunctions corresponding to different
 irreducible representations are always orthogonal.
 In the following, the theory will be focused on the zinc-blende crystal,
 for which the symmetry group of the Hamiltonian is 
\begin_inset Formula $T_{d}$
\end_inset

, the tetrahedral group.
 The elements are given by the 24 symmetry operations mapping a tetrahedron
 to itself.
 For an appropriate alignment and orientation, the symmetry operations are
 listed in Table 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "tab:Symmetry_operations_Td"

\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset Formula $T_{d}$
\end_inset

 has in total five distinct irreducible representations, which are commonly
 labeled as 
\begin_inset Formula $\Gamma_{1}$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $\Gamma_{2}$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $\Gamma_{12}$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $\Gamma_{15}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\Gamma_{25}$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset Formula $\Gamma_{1}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\Gamma_{2}$
\end_inset

 are one dimensional representations, 
\begin_inset Formula $\Gamma_{12}$
\end_inset

 is a two dimensional and 
\begin_inset Formula $\Gamma_{15}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\Gamma_{25}$
\end_inset

 are three dimensional.
 The basis functions for all irreducible representations are given in Table
 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "tab:Basis_functions_Td"

\end_inset

.
 The representation 
\begin_inset Formula $\Gamma_{1}$
\end_inset

 is the identity representation, also denoted as trivial representation,
 leaving the wavefunction invariant.
 An atomic wavefunction with 
\begin_inset Formula $s$
\end_inset

-like symmetry transforms accordingly, i.e.
 is left unchanged under the action of the elements of the group 
\begin_inset Formula $T_{d}$
\end_inset

.
 An example of the 
\begin_inset Formula $\Gamma_{1}$
\end_inset

 representation is given by the conduction band at the 
\begin_inset Formula $\Gamma$
\end_inset

 point of 
